                'media_used' => '',
                'biography' => '<p>Maria Sibylla Merian is renowned for her botanical illustrations of European flora and fauna, as well as those she encountered in Dutch Suriname. She was born in Frankfurt am Main in 1647. In 1665, Merian married the painter Johann Andreas Graff.</p><p>Her first book of natural illustrations was published in 1675, and she produced a volume on caterpillars in 1679. After many relocations to tend to sick family members, as well as a stint in a Labadist community in Friesland, Merian’s husband divorced her in 1692. In 1699, she journeyed to Dutch Suriname, where she stayed until malaria forced her to return to the Dutch Republic in 1701. Merian died in Amsterdam in 1717, after a long career filled with numerous publications of insects, plants, and other natural illustrations.</p>',
